    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5ad337e2-f9de-4d9d-b972-3fbdb793e7ef",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 7-year-old girl who appears tired and clingy, sitting close to her parent and swallowing carefully because of throat pain. Her face is mildly flushed, and she speaks in a softer voice than usual because talking makes her throat hurt. Over the last two days she has had a sore throat, low-grade fever, reduced appetite, discomfort when eating solid foods, and intermittent stomach ache, though she is still sipping water and taking small bites of soft foods. She has no obvious respiratory distress, but she occasionally coughs lightly and clears her throat.\n\nAt baseline, {patientName} is an active school-age child who enjoys drawing, playground games, reading early chapter books, and weekly beginner dance class. She attends primary school and after-school care, where several classmates have recently had colds and sore throats, and she also sings with her class during assemblies and indoor music periods, which brings her into close contact with other children. She lives with her mother, father, and an older brother in a smoke-free home, and the family keeps a structured routine with school, after-school care, and weekend visits with grandparents.\n\nHer parent reports that she was well until the current illness began abruptly after school. Since then, she has been more fatigued than usual, less interested in meals, and somewhat irritable, especially at bedtime. She has been sleeping a little more but wakes intermittently asking for water. There has been no drooling, no muffled \"hot potato\" voice, and no neck stiffness. She remains interactive, consolable, and able to drink.\n\nSocially and developmentally, {patientName} is age-appropriate, with good school performance and normal peer interactions. She participates in group school activities and dance, shares classroom materials with peers, and often attends indoor after-school programs during cold season, all of which increase exposure to common respiratory infections. Her parents are attentive and medically reliable, bringing her for assessment because the sore throat, fever, and stomach discomfort have persisted beyond a day and are affecting eating and activity."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:b7289be3-3ca1-49a1-844e-739d60c421a7",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has mild seasonal allergic rhinitis with intermittent nasal congestion and mouth-breathing during allergy seasons, which can contribute to throat irritation and susceptibility to pharyngeal symptoms. She has otherwise met developmental milestones appropriately and is up to date on routine childhood immunizations. She has had the usual minor childhood illnesses, including occasional viral upper respiratory infections, and her parent recalls two prior self-limited sore throat episodes over the last 18 months, both managed at home without hospitalization or confirmed streptococcal infection.\n\nHer parent reports no prior hospitalizations and no history of airway compromise. She has not had recent travel, and there are known sick contacts at school and in after-school care with upper respiratory symptoms. As a school-aged child in a crowded classroom and after-school setting, she has frequent close exposure to respiratory pathogens, which is a common risk factor for acute pharyngitis. Oral intake has decreased during this illness because swallowing is painful, but urine output has remained adequate, suggesting mild illness without significant dehydration.\n\n{patientName} lives in a stable home environment with supportive caregivers. There is no exposure to tobacco smoke at home. She is physically active for her age, attends school regularly, and generally sleeps well, although she is prone to dry throat discomfort after sleeping with her mouth open during periods of nasal allergy symptoms. Her regular medications include cetirizine during allergy flares and sodium fluoride supplementation; cetirizine can occasionally contribute to mild dry mouth or throat dryness, though it is not the primary cause of the current illness. No immunodeficiency, congenital disorder, or other major predisposing condition is known.\n\nFamily history is notable for her older brother having had multiple childhood sore throat infections, including one documented streptococcal pharyngitis episode, and her mother reports frequent throat infections as a child. This family pattern does not imply a genetic disorder but supports shared exposure patterns and a history of similar illness within the household."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
